item.title: China Launches Initiative to Set Global Data-Security Rules
item.description: China is launching its own initiative to set global standards on data security, countering U.S. efforts to persuade like-minded countries to ringfence their networks from Chinese technology.

item.title: Final Saudi Verdict Spares Khashoggi Killers From Execution
item.description: A Saudi court reduced the death sentences of five men convicted in the killing of dissident journalist Jamal Khashoggi and handed shorter sentences to three other nationals, in a case that drove a wedge between Saudi Arabia’s heir apparent and the West.

item.title: Belarus Opposition Leader Has Been Abducted, Colleagues Say
item.description: Belarus’s opposition says one of its leaders, Maria Kalesnikava, was abducted after weeks of protests against President Lukashenko.

item.title: As Poisoned Putin Critic Is Awakened From Coma, Germany Hints at Russia Pipeline Sanctions
item.description: German leader Angela Merkel hasn’t ruled out sanctions on the Nord Stream 2 pipeline with Russia over the poisoning of Alexei Navalny, who was roused from a coma Monday.

item.title: Israel Plans Overnight Curfew as Coronavirus Cases Surge
item.description: Schools will also be closed in dozens of cities and towns hit hard by the coronavirus, as Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu faces growing pressure to contain a rapid upsurge in infections.

item.title: FBI Sweep of China Researchers Leads to Cat-and-Mouse Tactics
item.description: A search by U.S. authorities for Chinese researchers with ties to China’s military is leading to intensifying cat-and-mouse tactics involving what prosecutors say are foiled escapes, evidence tossed into a dumpster and a chase through an airport.
